entry.title: Re-enable kRestrictCanAccessDataForOriginToUIThread
entry.content:
This CL re-enables Citadel checks in ChildProcessSecurityPolicy. See

dependent CLs (CL:5005884 and CL:5021611) for prerequisite work that

was required for this. In particular, the

RequestFileSetCheckedInCanRequestURL kill switch from CL:5005884 is

added as a requirement for the policy function,

ShouldRestrictCanAccessDataForOriginToUIThread(), which determines

whether or not it's ok to assume that CanAccessDataForOrigin() can

only be called on the UI thread, and if not, skip Citadel checks on

the IO thread. At this point, there is no known code that exercises

CanAccessDataForOrigin() outside of the UI thread and/or relies on

skipped Citadel checks either in production or in tests, though if the

kill switch were activated, this would be needed for the

PrepareDropDataForChildProcess_LocalFiles test.

entry.title: [remoting] Support fractional-coordinates without any screen_id.
entry.content:
With multi-stream, the client has a mapping between each video-stream

and its corresponding screen_id. The client uses this when sending

fractional coordinates in mouse or touch events.



With single-stream, the client does not have direct knowledge of the

screen_id for the stream.



So this CL enables the client to provide fractional coordinates without

a screen_id. For the scaling calculation, the host will use the

appropriate bounds and offset for the content being displayed by the

stream.

entry.title: Disable ALLOW_MISALIGNED in third_party/unrar
entry.content:
This fixes a host of UBSan errors, such as this one:

https://luci-milo.appspot.com/ui/inv/build-8764440332290274033/test-results?q=FileAnalyzerTest.RarAnalysisResultMetric&sortby=&groupby=



Although the underlying architecture may allow unaligned access, C and

C++ themselves do not allow this. Rather, unaligned loads should be

written with either memcpy, or by endian-agnostic reassembling of values

with shifts and ORs. Modern compilers recognize these patterns and

generate the unaligned load anyway.



There are a couple places where, depending on inlining, the compiler may

not be able to generate the same code. E.g. this function requires the

compiler know that `dest` cannot alias `arg1` or `arg2`.

https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:third_party/unrar/src/rijndael.cpp;drc=b86eab797178b986437ab3db265cceabf0b0496a;l=22



(It would be possible to write that in a way that is both

well-defined and encourages the compiler to load 4 bytes at a time.

Though we'd actually want it to load 16 bytes at a time with SIMD

instructions.)



But I assume unrar is not a hot path for us. If it were, we should

replace that file with calls to BoringSSL anyway, which has actually

optimized implementations. (Rijndael is the original name of AES.)

entry.title: Remove alignment requirements on source_image_ in BrowserThemePack
entry.content:
BrowserThemePack aliases various types into an underlying buffer. A

priori, this is not safe because types must be aligned, but all the

types are wrapped in `#pragma pack` to remove their alignment

requirements.



Strictly speaking, this is still not allowed in C++ due to strict

aliasing requirements, but Chromium disables strict aliasing and

attempting to fix this would require rewriting a lot of code.



However, `source_images_` just has type `int`, and `#pragma pack` only

applies to types defined in the region of code. As a result,

`source_images_` still has the usual alignment requirements of `int`.

UBSan flagged a violation of this here:



https://luci-milo.appspot.com/ui/inv/build-8764440332290274033/test-results?q=BrowserThemePackTest.HiDpiThemeTest&sortby=&groupby=



To avoid this problem, wrap the int in a struct. `#pragma pack` then

applies and we remove the alignment requirement.

entry.title: [wpt-importer] Do not merge TestExpectations with the same results
entry.content:
Calling `SystemConfigurationEditor.update_versions(...)` once with

multiple versions gives the same result as updating versions one at a

time [0], so merging test results into a more deeply nested

intermediate structure is unnecessary.



Also, `SystemConfigurationEditor.merge_versions(...)` only needs to be

entry.title: [window-splitting] Fix splitting on extended displays.
entry.content:
There were two issues that caused the bug:



1) When repositioning the windows on drag completion, the bounds were

set using `SetBounds()`, which expected values in root window

coordinates, but the values passed in were in screen coordinates. This

was changed to use `SetBoundsInScreen()`.



2) When dragging a window across different displays, the root window

changes between the call to `Drag()` and `CompleteDrag()`, which changes

the frame of reference of "parent" coordinates. The code was storing the

last drag location in parent coordinates between the two calls, so when

the value was converted back to screen coordinates later, it resulted in

a different screen location. The fix was to store the last drag location

in screen coordinates instead.



Added tests to exercise both conditions above.

entry.title: Enable echo cancellation for AAudio input
entry.content:
This CL adds Echo Cancellation support for AAudio inputs, by properly

setting the input preset on the stream.



We use AAUDIO_INPUT_PRESET_VOICE_COMMUNICATION when the

AudioParameters::ECHO_CANCELLER effect bit is set, and

AAUDIO_INPUT_PRESET_CAMCORDER in all other cases.



We choose the *CAMCORDER preset instead of the default preset of

*VOICE_RECOGNITION for two reasons:

entry.title: Remove `will_cause_resize` from WebContents::ExitFullscreen()
entry.content:
This CL fixes a regression on Mac that if a web page enters the tab

fullscreen mode and then exits fullscreen by system controls (keyboard

shortcuts or window control buttons), the page becomes

fullscreen-in-tab. This issue was caused by the browser not sending

a resize message to the renderer after browser has exited fullscreen.

Specifically, the resize message isn't sent because the browser

is told that there will by another resize event and skips this message

when `will_cause_resize` is True.



This issue can be solved by removing the `will_cause_resize` parameter

from WebContents::ExitFullscreen() so that a resize message is sent

every time this function is called to exit fullscreen.



The `will_cause_resize` flag was initially added to restore the

scroll position when toggling fullscreen mode crrev.com/1488653002

However, the scroll restoration was later removed because of its

complexity by crrev.com/c/1195714 and this flag wasn't cleaned up

at that time.



There are several places where a True value is passed to

`will_cause_resize` i.e. exit fullscreen when showing a printer pop

up dialog. These use cases shouldn't be affected by having another

page resize.

entry.title: Refactor blink signal to autofill on form related changes
entry.content:
Currently blink sends a signal to Autofill about form related elements

being added/removed in a single signal. There exist several problems

with the current mechanism:



-Blink calls it when a ListedElement is reassociated to another form,

which is neither an add nor a remove operation.

-The type of operation that fired the signal is lost (add/remove)

-The actual element affected is lost on the way to AutofillAgent.



This CL:

-Adds an enum WebFormRelatedChange to identify the actual type of change

that happened. This will be used on Autofill side because not all change

types will be handled the same way.



-Adds a `kReassociate` value to distinguish reassociation from additions

and removals.



-Renames the function DidAddOrRemoveFormRelatedElement to

DidChangeFormRelatedElementDynamically to reflect that this signal is

not limited to additions and removals (will later also be used for

elements becoming hidden).



-Passes the element changed as a parameter of the signal all the way to

AutofillAgent. This can be used to deduce the nature of the element.

(Form vs Field) and for submission tracking purposes.

entry.title: Always pass DriveFS mount path from ash -> lacros with no /root
entry.content:
GetMountPointPath() and OnMountPointPathChanged() were both passing

the DriveFS 'mount path' to lacros with /root appended, which is

the path for the MyDrive directory, and not the whole of driveFS,

which has other subdirectories like /team_drives.



Other code refers to the /media/fuse/drivefs- (no /root) as

'mount path' so we should do the same here.



Now ash always passes the DriveFS mount path without /root, and

callers in lacros can add /root if they want to deal with the

MyDrive directory specifically.



There were two ways to get the mount path in lacros, one in the

lacros -> ash direction (GetMountPointPath()), and a newer one in

the ash -> lacros direction (OnMountPointPathChanged()) which

pushes changes to lacros when the path changed in ash.



chrome_paths_lacros.h maintains local state in lacros based on

OnMountPointPathChanged(), which means we always have the latest

path stashed in lacros anyway, meaning there's not much use for

GetMountPointPath() anymore, which is asynchronous, making it

less convenient to use when we need the mount path.



This CL removes uses of GetMountPointPath() and marks it

deprecated. This is also convenient as we don't have to deal with

version skew, as we are only relying on the change in behaviour

for the ash -> lacros direction. All versions of lacros that

will be used with this new behaviour in ash will also have the

new lacros-side code which does not expect the /root dir.



This fixes a bug where the Google Drive MyDrive root folder

would not work when set as the default downloads location in

lacros. It was getting filtered out by

DownloadPrefs::SanitizeDownloadTargetPath(), which was trying

to check if /media/fuse/drivefs-/root was a child of

itself (rather than a child of just .../drivefs-).

entry.title: [AsyncSB] Set showed_interstitial to true only when the top-document navigation has not yet committed
entry.content:
showed_interstitial affects whether the error code returned in

CancelWithError is net::ERR_BLOCKED_BY_CLIENT or net::ERR_ABORTED[1].

If the error is ERR_BLOCKED_BY_CLIENT, the error page will be

returned in SafeBrowsingNavigationThrottle[2].



Given that SBNThrottle is only in affect if the navigation is primary

main frame, and the fact that LoadPostCommitErrorPage is also called for

delayed warning or nested frames and WebContents, I think

showed_interstitial should depend on load_post_commit_error_page

instead of solely on IsMainPageLoadBlocked.



In practice, this CL has the following behavioral change:

* For delayed warnings, showed_intertitial was true but now false.

This is ok, because delayed warnings are triggered through

LoadPostCommitErrorPage anyway. It doesn't depend on SBNThrottle.

* For nested frames and WebContents, showed_interstitial was true

but now false. This is also ok, because SBNThrottle doesn't act

on none primary main frame navigation, so the error returned in

BrowserUrlLoaderThrottle is essentially equivalent.

* For other scenarios, there is no behavioral change, because

load_post_commit_error_page and !IsMainPageLoadBlocked are

equivalent.

entry.title: Create additional pages for trailing monolithic overflow.
entry.content:
We used to synthesize additional pages during printing to encompass such

overflow, but it's easier and cleaner to actually just generate as many

page fragments as we need during layout.



Improve the existing monolithic overflow handling to achieve this.

What's new with this change is that we may have to generate additional

pages to encompass all overflow, even when there might not be any

subsequent descendants to add. The previous implementation only made

sure that subsequent content wouldn't overlap with in-flow monolithic

overflow, so it didn't bother to continue once we were past all content

in the main fragmentation flow.



We also need to include the overflow inside the overflowing monolithic

element, to get enough pages. The border box of the monolithic content

may overflow fragmentainers, but the layout overflow of the monolithic

content may overflow even more fragmentainers. Add a test for this (it

also used to pass without this change).



No behavior changes intended.

entry.title: media: add flag to disable WebGPU SharedImage
entry.content:
Flex supports devices with legacy AMD GPUs that do not support the

ANDROID_native_fence_sync EGL extension, required for synchronizing

WebGPU on OzoneImageBacking with other write streams. This change

prevents MailboxVideoFrameConverter from committing to webgpu zero

copy support, which signals to OzoneImageBackingFactory that WebGPU

will not be used on the SharedImage. As a result, WebGPU will not work

on the device. However, it was not working anyways and since this is a

legacy device, that support will probably not be added. I do not

outright disable WebGPU thru gpu/config/webgpu_blocklist.h as

there isn't any code in Ozone|MailboxVideoFrameConverter which

checks if WebGPU is enabled, so this wouldn't do anything to fix

the graphics regression. More Flex devices will be added to this

flag once testing is done.

entry.title: Display coverage even for fuzzers which fail.
entry.content:
Previously, we ran each fuzzer for its whole corpus in one go. This was

quick, but if the fuzzer exited due to any one input, this resulted in

us failing to write out any coverage information for the fuzzer at all.



Since some fuzzers result in crashes, this meant 122 fuzzers were

displaying no coverage.



This change detects the case where the initial bulk run results in a

crash, and then runs the fuzzer individually against each input in the

hopes that some of them don't crash.



So, how much longer will this all take?



We currently have 122 fuzzers which are erroring out. Let's assume each

case takes 0.3 seconds.



"Worst" case = 1000 test cases * 122 fuzzers * 0.3 seconds = 10 hours

longer to run the job



But let's assume that these fuzzers only have to run 400 test cases in

order to get 200 valid traces, which seems more likely.



So likely case = 400 test cases * 122 fuzzers * 0.3 seconds = 4 hours

longer to run the job



In practice, the 0.3 estimate might be wrong, we'll see.
